Explanation of Bootstrap Classes Used
Navbar Classes:

navbar: Base class for the navbar.
navbar-expand-lg: Makes the navbar expandable on large screens.
navbar-light: Applies a light background and dark text.
bg-light: Sets the background color of the navbar to light.
nav-link: Styles the links within the navbar.
Grid System:

container: Centers the content and adds padding.
row: Creates a horizontal group of columns.
col-md-4: Defines a column that occupies 4 out of 12 grid units on medium-sized screens and larger.
Card Classes:

card: Styles the div as a card component.
card-body: Adds padding inside the card.
card-title: Styles the title of the card.
card-text: Styles the text within the card.
Button Classes:

btn: Base class for buttons.
btn-primary, btn-success, btn-warning: Specific button styles representing different colors and meanings.
How Classes Contribute to the Design
Consistency: Bootstrap provides a consistent look and feel across different components with its predefined classes, making it easier to create a cohesive design.
Responsive Layout: The grid system allows for fluid layouts that adjust to different screen sizes, ensuring the design works well on mobile, tablet, and desktop devices.
Flexibility: Bootstrap's classes allow for customization and styling without needing extensive custom CSS, speeding up development time.
Conclusion
Bootstrap is a powerful framework that simplifies the process of building responsive web designs. By utilizing its grid system, predefined classes, and components, developers can create visually appealing and functional web pages efficiently. The example above demonstrates a simple layout with a navbar, grid system, and buttons, highlighting how Bootstrap's classes contribute to a consistent and responsive design.






